# IV. New cryptographic constructions

---

## 1. Dual-Sign Capability Composition (DSCC)

We need a capability that only exists when both principals contribute authorization.

### Construction

For object \(m\), action \(a\), destination \(d\), purpose \(p\), expiry \(T\):

User signs:
\[
\sigma_u = \text{Sign}_{sk_u}(H(m\|a\|d\|p\|T\|C))
\]

Third party signs:
\[
\sigma_t = \text{Sign}_{sk_t}(H(m\|a\|d\|p\|T\|C))
\]

Capability:
\[
\chi = (\sigma_u,\sigma_t,\text{meta})
\]

Verifier accepts iff:
- both signatures valid
- same payload
- contract \(C\) active
- not revoked

This is simple but fundamental.

### Better version
Threshold capability with policy hash:
\[
\chi = \text{AggregateSig}(\{\sigma_i\}_{i \in \Omega(m,a)})
\]

This lets policies generalize to many parties.

---

## 2. Rights-Locked Release Encryption

A release package should only decrypt if dual approval exists.

Encrypt package key \(k\) under a policy:

\[
\mathcal{P} = u \land t \land \text{purpose}=p \land \text{expiry}<T
\]

Use attribute-based encryption or threshold re-encryption so decryption only works if policy tokens from both sides are present.

This is not entirely new cryptography, but we need a new application-layer protocol:
- contract-bound
- action-specific
- revocable
- audit-linked

---

## 3. Rights-Preserving Export Proof

The human must be able to export their vault while preserving locked status.

Need a proof object:

\[
\pi_{\text{export}}(E) = \text{Proof}\big(
E \text{ contains all objects and rights metadata, unchanged}
\big)
\]

This is a verifiable portability proof:
- export complete
- rights tags preserved
- no hidden stripping

This is new at the protocol layer.

