# VI. New theorems / principles we should define

---

## Theorem 1 — Custody-Control Separation
A principal may retain complete cryptographic custody of memory while action authority over subsets is jointly governed.

This is more of an architectural theorem than a proof-heavy theorem, but we should define it formally.

---

## Theorem 2 — Information Inheritance Principle
If a derivative \(y\) retains nontrivial conditional mutual information about protected source \(x\) beyond public baseline \(B\), then \(y\) is not rights-independent of \(x\).

\[
I(x;y \mid B) > \epsilon \implies y \text{ inherits some rights burden from } x
\]

This is huge. This should be one of the constitutional ideas in the system.

---

## Theorem 3 — Minimal Governance Disclosure
There exists a review representation \(R^*\) that minimizes disclosure subject to decision sufficiency, given a contract decision family.

\[
R^* = \arg\min_R I(M;R) \;\text{s.t.}\; I(R;D)\ge \tau
\]

This becomes the target for review packet optimization.

---

## Theorem 4 — Veto Safety
For any action requiring 2-of-2 approval, if the capability composition operator only validates under joint signatures, no unilateral actor can produce a valid external release capability.

This is cryptographic and straightforward.

